<|startoftext|>Headline:Pakistan's army tells civilians not to attack after four wounded
Content: "WASHINGTON/NEW YORK (Reuters) - Pakistani soldier Sajwani was wounded in a U.S.-led battle with Indian-American-American co-worker Sajeel, his family said on Tuesday, but was told  not to attack  after four of his relatives said he appeared to have been hit by a car bomb in a U.S.-led battle in a Pakistani village. The injured and their families have since received a series of emails and photographs suggesting the wounded, Sajeehul Haq, 24, was hit by a roadside bomb while driving home, the family s attorney, Aamir Khan, said.   The family says Sajeehul was seriously wounded but said one of his relatives told him three weeks ago that the injured soldier s injuries had caused severe brain damage, resulting in irreversible damage. He had no additional information about his health. He was found at about 12:15 p.m. in a parking lot in a village in the Karmy neighborhood of Khandawala Sindh, a mile southeast of Lahore, the family said. Two family members, including Haq s brother-in-law Mohammad Iqbal and a cousin of his, are among many wounded Pakistani-American Indians by roadside bombs launched in recent months.      In July, three Indian-Americans were killed in a bomb attack in Pakistan s eastern city of Lahore.  Pakistani Army sources told Reuters that the blast may have been planted by Haq s cousins after he had returned home to India from a U.S. training-camp in Afghanistan when he was wounded in the leg by a landmine bomb. The family is seeking unspecified compensation for the injuries of his parents, but he has no idea who he was. ",<|endoftext|>
